"Informed Consent Form for Extraction Based Fixed Orthodontic Treatment Possible risks of orthognathic surgery As with other surgeries, jaw surgeries also carry certain risks. These can be simple risks or they can be deadly. It is very important that you understand well some of the risks that may develop after jaw tip surgery. Surgery and other procedures to be performed: An incision will be made through the mouth or over the skin to reach the lower jaw bone. In addition, if it is necessary to take bone or tissue from another part of your body, it may be necessary to make an incision from another part of your body. The mandible will be corrected by cutting the bone at the appropriate place osteotomy and fixed using one or more of the following: - Titanium plates andor screws, fusible plate andor screws, sutures, metal arches and wires applied to teeth, bone, cartilage and tissues taken from your body, bone, cartilage, bone paste, bone powder, silicone from another human or animal, alloplastic materials such as porous hydroxyapatite, methyl methacrylate, titanium mesh Unless there is a problem, these materials can stay in place for a lifetime. If problems arise, a second surgery may be required to remove them. At the end of the operation or later, the lower jaw and the upper jaw can be locked for 7-10 days Intermaxillary fixation. During this period, only watery foods should be fed. If there is difficulty in breathing or nausea, the rubbers applied for the fixation may be cut. 1. Side effects that may develop due to any surgical intervention: a. Discomfortpost-operative pain from the surgery itself b. Edema Swelling c. Bleeding d. Numbness 2. Injury of branch of facial nerve Facial nerve, 3. Giving blood: Bleeding in surgery or after surgery that requires an autologous donor or blood transfusion may occur, 4. Recurrence or need for additional procedures, 5. Infection: The wound may recur, but it usually resolves with antibiotics and local treatment with washing., 6. 